            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="40"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_16526621' href='vote?id=16526621&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16525087'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=klondike_" class="hnuser">klondike_</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=16526621">7 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_16526621"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="2" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 16526621)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">This has to do with the starter mechanism. All florescent tubes need a starter, including CFLs. Industrial&#x2F;commercial florescent lights take a few seconds to warm up, often with some flickering. For home use people want their light bulbs to start up fast, so manufacturers put quicker starters in CFLs at the expense of longevity.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=16526621&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16525087%2316526621">reply</a></u>
